child, and my parents are from Lithuania.

02:10.480 --> 02:13.480
The refugees from World War two.

02:14.400 --> 02:17.880
We came over here in 1949,

02:20.160 --> 02:21.960
to Gary, Indiana,

02:21.960 --> 02:24.960
and we've been there since,

02:25.840 --> 02:28.840
Why did they move to, Gary, Indiana?

02:30.800 --> 02:35.040
My father found a sponsor,
a distant relative.

02:35.040 --> 02:38.200
We sponsor this to come over.

02:39.600 --> 02:42.600
Western Europe had millions of refugees,

02:43.520 --> 02:46.520
who are seeking to be resettled.

02:46.560 --> 02:49.840
And then my father found a distant
relative who's for service,

02:50.400 --> 02:51.360
to come to Gary.

02:51.360 --> 02:55.120
And that's where my parents stayed
until they retired.

02:55.120 --> 02:58.120
And then they moved to Florida.

03:00.840 --> 03:02.120
What was your experience

03:02.120 --> 03:05.120
growing up in Gary, Indiana?

03:08.040 --> 03:09.560
Well, it's kind of complicated.

03:09.560 --> 03:12.520
Gary was at that time,

03:12.520 --> 03:15.880
a very multicultural, very ethnic 70,

03:17.240 --> 03:19.840
that had a very good economy

03:19.840 --> 03:23.040
and a good economy
based on the steel industry.

03:23.880 --> 03:26.880
And, that's
what brought a lot of people to Gary.

03:27.240 --> 03:33.480
But starting in about the 1970s, the
economy started to collapse and the city,

03:34.560 --> 03:37.880
started to decay and disintegrate.

03:37.880 --> 03:42.200
And today,
I think it's like 25%, abandoned.

03:43.080 --> 03:46.640
So but at that time,
there were a lot of people who were there.

03:46.640 --> 03:48.760
It was called the 20th Century City.

03:48.760 --> 03:51.720
It was actually built by U.S. steel.

03:51.720 --> 03:54.080
You know,
I think it was the first Plant City

03:54.080 --> 03:57.080
or 20th century,

03:57.920 --> 04:01.000
so there were a lot of people there,
a lot of ethnics, especially,

04:02.040 --> 04:04.000
not just Europe, a lot from Europe,

04:04.000 --> 04:07.320
but also a big, black migration
from America.

04:07.320 --> 04:10.320
South.

04:10.320 --> 04:13.320
And they were all there
mingling together in the mills.

04:13.600 --> 04:16.600
So it was kind of a very interesting
community.

04:19.360 --> 04:20.960
Hundreds of different languages

04:20.960 --> 04:27.400
spoken, different cultures different
or those ethnic organizations.

04:27.400 --> 04:31.440
So that was the sort of the landscape
that I grew up in.

04:32.440 --> 04:34.520
But the cultural landscape.

04:34.520 --> 04:36.840
So it was like a melting pot in a way.

04:38.200 --> 04:39.840
In a way, yeah.

04:39.840 --> 04:40.600
Melting pot.

04:40.600 --> 04:43.680
Somebody else
describe it as a salad bowl, but. Oh,

04:45.000 --> 04:47.160
like all mixed together.

04:47.160 --> 04:48.240
Yeah.

04:48.240 --> 04:51.240
But still retaining their individual,

04:52.440 --> 04:54.320
Vegetable

04:54.320 --> 04:56.720
characteristics
like their own like identity.

04:56.720 --> 04:59.720
So and everything

04:59.960 --> 05:02.240
the area that you lived in in particular

05:02.240 --> 05:05.560
were there other like Lithuanian refugees
living there as well.

05:05.560 --> 05:08.240
Or was it the city.

05:08.240 --> 05:11.240
There was an area,

05:11.640 --> 05:15.880
13th and Grant,
where there seem to have been

05:15.880 --> 05:18.880
a lot of lost wages, but there was also

05:18.960 --> 05:21.920
a Lithuanian Catholic parish

05:21.920 --> 05:24.920
that was founded,
I think, in the early 1900s.

05:25.800 --> 05:29.800
And it in essence was, well,
it was the church,

05:29.800 --> 05:32.800
but it also had a school,

05:32.880 --> 05:34.560
and it became kind of,

05:34.560 --> 05:37.560
like a community center for the community.

05:38.280 --> 05:39.600
And that's where I went to school.

05:39.600 --> 05:43.120
I went to, Catholic school taught by nuns.

05:45.240 --> 05:48.520
And then after that, I went to, Andrean
High School,

05:48.520 --> 05:52.320
which was I was in the first class
of the new building.

05:52.480 --> 05:55.280
So not that,

05:55.280 --> 05:57.840
it was taught by nuns and priests

05:57.840 --> 06:00.840
or I had priests or teachers.

06:02.320 --> 06:03.000
Would you say you.

06:03.000 --> 06:06.000
So, are you a practicing Catholic today?

06:06.920 --> 06:09.200
No, no.

06:09.200 --> 06:11.520
What was your experience with in school,
then?

06:11.520 --> 06:13.920
Favorite subjects? Favorite teachers?

06:13.920 --> 06:16.920
The people that you were with,

06:20.240 --> 06:22.120
It was not a very good education.

06:22.120 --> 06:25.120
It was basically based on,

06:25.560 --> 06:28.960
sort of Catholic morality.

06:28.960 --> 06:33.800
It was just a lot of lecturing
about religious matters.

06:33.800 --> 06:36.800
We were very disappointed as kids
because that was,

06:37.760 --> 06:40.760
started
what was called the space age, where,

06:42.280 --> 06:44.520
the first satellite, Sputnik.

06:44.520 --> 06:48.320
The Russians set the spirit
in the center of the space.

06:49.560 --> 06:52.920
There were all this, rocketry with,

06:54.240 --> 06:55.440
the Defense Department.

06:55.440 --> 06:56.920
So it was this.

06:56.920 --> 07:00.520
I see it as the beginning
of this technology, technological age.

07:00.720 --> 07:02.560
We're still learning today.

07:02.560 --> 07:04.640
And we were very excited about it.

07:04.640 --> 07:07.680
And we actually tried to read up

07:07.680 --> 07:10.960
on buying all kinds of magazines,
even in grade school, you know?

07:11.160 --> 07:16.280
So education and all that was
very important, even at that early age.

07:16.280 --> 07:19.480
We we wanted very much
to get out of that great school

07:20.480 --> 07:23.400
and get to a better education.

07:23.400 --> 07:26.800
So did you have an interest

07:26.800 --> 07:29.800
in like, science and space yourself or,

07:29.840 --> 07:32.480
was I just like a product of the time
and everything?

07:32.480 --> 07:32.680
Yeah.

07:32.680 --> 07:36.680
I mean, I did very much and to this day,
I really like

07:36.680 --> 07:39.680
reading about science and technology.

07:42.000 --> 07:44.840
What did you go to for school?

07:44.840 --> 07:45.840
After your high school?

07:47.840 --> 07:48.320
I went to

07:48.320 --> 07:52.200
Indiana University with the intention
of becoming an astronomer,

07:52.440 --> 07:55.840
which didn't work out
because I was not good at math,

07:56.720 --> 07:59.720
but, eventually,

07:59.920 --> 08:02.360
I settled on Slavic studies,

08:02.360 --> 08:05.360
Slavic languages.

08:06.280 --> 08:07.960
It took,

08:07.960 --> 08:10.960
Russian, Polish and,

08:11.400 --> 08:14.040
along with German,

08:14.040 --> 08:15.880
I think because of where

08:15.880 --> 08:18.880
I grew up in, Gary,
I was so interested in languages.

08:19.240 --> 08:22.800
Even in high school,
I took, Spanish and Latin,

08:24.000 --> 08:25.960
and then and, and I you

08:25.960 --> 08:29.640
which were was related to, to the U.S.

08:29.640 --> 08:32.640
Army, language school

08:32.840 --> 08:36.360
to this very day in the university
has a very,

08:37.520 --> 08:40.280
great,

08:40.280 --> 08:43.320
well,
many courses in many different languages.

08:43.320 --> 08:46.200
And I took advantage of that,

08:46.200 --> 08:48.440
studying Slavic.

08:48.440 --> 08:52.520
And then,
I spent the year in Poland in person.

08:52.520 --> 08:56.760
I said, I'm at school at university.

08:59.240 --> 09:00.520
And then eventually,

09:01.520 --> 09:04.520
and that up in grad school

09:04.760 --> 09:07.760
and in the folklore department,

09:10.040 --> 09:10.480
actually

09:10.480 --> 09:13.760
interested
in more sort of holistic ethnography.

09:13.880 --> 09:16.880
But it's not just the folklore.

09:17.240 --> 09:19.240
I also took more languages.

09:19.240 --> 09:22.240
I was involved in,

09:22.520 --> 09:23.840
and the really county

09:23.840 --> 09:26.840
Department of semiotics, such a,

09:27.840 --> 09:30.760
so that was sort of my experience.

09:30.760 --> 09:33.760
And, you.

09:34.080 --> 09:38.080
Do you think that your family background
led you to want to study like,

09:38.080 --> 09:42.400
Slavic languages and get into that
cultural, like side of your studies?

09:43.880 --> 09:44.840
Yeah.

09:44.840 --> 09:48.920
I, my parents were like,
you know, trilingual in all languages,

09:48.920 --> 09:51.920
and everybody around me,

09:52.760 --> 09:55.400
in the city was like a private,

09:55.400 --> 09:58.400
for example, this is sort of,

09:58.680 --> 10:00.480
but I think it's pretty good.

10:00.480 --> 10:03.480
Example
where we lived on Harrison Boulevard.

10:04.040 --> 10:08.280
I could almost remember every house
on our side of the street,

10:09.640 --> 10:11.360
except for two.

10:11.360 --> 10:13.680
And they each one
was a different ethnic group.

10:13.680 --> 10:17.400
But I can remember it was Serbian, Slavic,

10:17.760 --> 10:20.560
Lithuanian, Italian.

10:20.560 --> 10:23.600
I don't remember the Lithuanian,

10:23.760 --> 10:26.720
I don't remember Mexican, Slovak.

10:26.720 --> 10:29.760
Everybody on our street was an immigrant.

10:31.880 --> 10:34.880
And that whole area of Gary and,

10:35.280 --> 10:38.280
later I found out
it's called the Hungarian region.

10:38.320 --> 10:40.280
I didn't know that.

10:40.280 --> 10:42.960
So that just gives you kind of a snapshot

10:42.960 --> 10:45.960
of what Gary was like at that time.

10:49.120 --> 10:49.480
Going

10:49.480 --> 10:53.360
into your cultural
and linguistic traditions at home,

10:53.360 --> 10:57.320
what languages did you speak at home,
and are there any traditions

10:57.320 --> 11:01.160
or practices that you can think of that
your family practiced, like with you?

11:03.080 --> 11:04.560
We never spoke English at home.

11:04.560 --> 11:07.560
I was always Lithuanian. And,

11:08.880 --> 11:13.440
I think I was,
I was pretty American, except for,

11:14.640 --> 11:17.680
one holiday, which was Christmasy,

11:17.880 --> 11:20.880
which was a very important
for Lithuanians.

11:21.560 --> 11:24.560
The other big one was, Thanksgiving.

11:25.160 --> 11:28.160
This is my mother called it Turkey Day.

11:28.720 --> 11:31.240
So those two really stand out.

11:31.240 --> 11:35.040
But everything else was just,
you know, normal American.

11:36.760 --> 11:39.120
That Friday.

11:39.120 --> 11:42.000
Friday's
used to be also kind of interesting.

11:42.000 --> 11:44.880
Every bar in the region would,

11:44.880 --> 11:47.880
people go there to get, lake perch,

11:49.200 --> 11:52.440
coleslaw, lake perch, some fries and beer.

11:52.600 --> 11:55.600
And that was kind of a tradition
for a lot of people.

11:56.280 --> 11:59.400
And was that like,
the whole community came together

11:59.400 --> 12:02.840
to celebrate together
or like, individual family units did this?

12:03.960 --> 12:07.800
The Christmas Eve was a very much
a family, tradition

12:08.840 --> 12:11.640
of friends might come over,
but each family

12:11.640 --> 12:14.640
tried to have their own.

12:18.480 --> 12:21.480
So I know that you touched on this
already a bit, but just you,

12:22.680 --> 12:25.880
go into
the specific cultural background questions

12:26.160 --> 12:29.520
which cultural or ethnic heritages
do you identify with,

12:29.520 --> 12:32.520
and has your self-identification
changed over time?

12:34.520 --> 12:36.360
No, I mean, it's pretty much,

12:36.360 --> 12:39.360
I'm kind of, you know, I think

12:39.600 --> 12:44.440
what's what kind of person meaning one
part is ethnic, the other was American.

12:44.440 --> 12:47.440
So a combination of

12:47.760 --> 12:49.840
those things,

12:49.840 --> 12:51.680
I think a lot of

12:51.680 --> 12:55.440
that's like people feel the same,
you know, the

12:56.760 --> 12:59.280
they're Americans,
but they also have an ethnic

12:59.280 --> 13:02.280
background. So.

13:02.520 --> 13:03.520
Did you feel close

13:03.520 --> 13:06.520
to your Lithuanian heritage
growing up, or did you,

13:07.000 --> 13:10.080
because you basically grew up here
in the United States,

13:10.880 --> 13:14.080
was is that mostly what formed
your identity over time?

13:16.000 --> 13:17.400
Yeah, I feel close to it.

13:17.400 --> 13:20.400
I mean, the kids of,

13:21.320 --> 13:24.200
emigres or refugees like my parents.

13:25.520 --> 13:26.480
One of the things that was

13:26.480 --> 13:30.320
happening back in Europe,
this was postwar.

13:30.800 --> 13:32.160
My parents fled.

13:32.160 --> 13:36.040
What exactly what is happening

13:36.040 --> 13:39.040
today in Ukraine?

13:39.320 --> 13:42.320
It was it was really horrible. And,

13:43.000 --> 13:46.000
my uncle, for example,
my father's brother,

13:48.760 --> 13:52.120
I don't know why,
but they decided to stay, and they were

13:52.120 --> 13:55.520
they were, deported to Siberia
for ten years.

13:57.640 --> 14:00.040
On death trains or people freeze.

14:00.040 --> 14:03.200
I mean, horrible stories
and Lithuania alone.

14:03.200 --> 14:06.080
And I'm not talking about other countries
like Belarus.

14:06.080 --> 14:08.120
So a lot to your story.

14:08.120 --> 14:12.160
It was the when you are alone,
the estimates are between

14:12.160 --> 14:15.720
100 and maybe 300,000
people were deported.

14:15.960 --> 14:19.360
Siberia, at least 60,000 died.

14:20.160 --> 14:22.240
And so when these,

14:22.240 --> 14:24.280
refugees, like my parents

14:24.280 --> 14:27.280
escaped, they brought with them

14:27.480 --> 14:31.960
the idea that one day they will go back.

14:32.760 --> 14:34.560
And so they fled for their culture.

14:34.560 --> 14:35.760
You know, they supported the,

14:36.720 --> 14:38.400
the Lithuanian parachute,

14:38.400 --> 14:42.440
where everybody would meet for celebrate

14:42.440 --> 14:46.080
the first independence and, other kind of,

14:46.520 --> 14:50.040
they would teacher, for example,
I went there to Saturday school

14:51.120 --> 14:54.960
to, to keep, my Lithuania up.

14:55.120 --> 14:59.800
We learned how to dance and sing,
you know, of the Lithuanian, songs.

15:00.640 --> 15:03.720
And these parishes
were all through Carry On.

15:03.720 --> 15:06.720
It was just Lithuanian.

15:08.040 --> 15:10.000
They all did pretty much same thing.

15:10.000 --> 15:13.000
They wanted to keep alive their culture

15:13.800 --> 15:16.800
within the American landscape.

15:17.520 --> 15:21.120
So. Did you enjoy this?

15:21.120 --> 15:25.040
These, like, Saturday school sessions
to, like, get in touch with your culture?

15:25.040 --> 15:28.080
Or were you really young
and did it help me understand?

15:28.160 --> 15:30.560
I thought it was cool,
you know? Yeah. Different.

15:30.560 --> 15:33.240
Yeah.

15:33.240 --> 15:33.960
Same time.

15:33.960 --> 15:36.520
Also,

15:36.520 --> 15:39.800
the anti-immigrant, feeling was always
there.

15:39.880 --> 15:42.040
Just just as we see today.

15:44.480 --> 15:45.320
The maligning of

15:45.320 --> 15:48.320
immigrants by, you know, by MAGA Trump

15:49.280 --> 15:50.880
that's always been there.

15:50.880 --> 15:53.880
My earliest feelings, and I don't,

15:54.080 --> 15:56.320
I don't know where they're coming from,

15:56.320 --> 16:00.000
but somehow I'm being told
that I'm different.

16:00.720 --> 16:01.440
I'm not right.

16:01.440 --> 16:04.440
There's something wrong with me.

16:05.560 --> 16:07.560
I've always felt that, you know, with.

16:07.560 --> 16:08.560
But that's American.

16:08.560 --> 16:11.560
I mean, it has a long history

16:12.320 --> 16:14.880
of immigrants coming here.

16:14.880 --> 16:17.880
And they're told they need to assimilate,

16:18.240 --> 16:22.640
through my career of doing various
kind of cultural projects.

16:22.640 --> 16:26.160
I don't know how many people have
never told me the story that,

16:27.600 --> 16:29.920
my parents
didn't want me to learn the language

16:29.920 --> 16:32.920
because they wanted me to be successful.

16:32.960 --> 16:35.360
Meaning hide your ethnic identity.

16:35.360 --> 16:39.600
So for a lot of people,
it was a rejection of the old countries.

16:41.000 --> 16:42.480
For some of us,

16:42.480 --> 16:45.920
we rejoiced
what we had from the old country.

16:45.920 --> 16:48.400
What I never left, I was never born there.

16:48.400 --> 16:49.200
I was never left.

16:49.200 --> 16:52.240
But I grew up with the idea of returning
just really weird.

16:53.960 --> 16:56.120
And so eventually I sort of did.

16:56.120 --> 16:59.040
I went there a couple times,

16:59.040 --> 17:02.640
and now my wife is from Lithuania,
so we go back

17:02.840 --> 17:05.840
every once in a while.

17:06.800 --> 17:07.680
You just answer

17:07.680 --> 17:10.880
my next question,
which was, have you gone back

17:10.880 --> 17:13.400
and what was your feeling
when you went back?

17:13.400 --> 17:14.760
Did you?

17:14.760 --> 17:16.720
Yeah. Let me know what you were feeling.

17:16.720 --> 17:18.920
Well, it was
it was really a special moment

17:18.920 --> 17:22.280
because I spent a year in Poland,
which is right next to Lithuania.

17:22.880 --> 17:27.960
And then, I was happy
because of all this Russification.

17:27.960 --> 17:30.480
It was a,
you know, just a brutal dictatorship.

17:31.440 --> 17:31.800
But I

17:31.800 --> 17:35.360
braved myself and got a visa to Lithuania.

17:35.880 --> 17:38.880
It was limited to three days.

17:39.080 --> 17:42.080
By then, my uncle and his family,

17:42.720 --> 17:45.720
had come back to the winter from Siberia.

17:46.240 --> 17:48.720
So I was going to be the first person
to meet them.

17:48.720 --> 17:51.720
That was really an emotional moment.

17:51.800 --> 17:54.800
Oh, excuse me.

17:55.560 --> 17:58.800
Did you meet any of your other family
